{
  "answer": "Step 1: The mathematical expression for an ARMA(2,1) model is given by:\\\\\\ Y_t = c + \\phi_1 Y_{t-1} + \\phi_2 Y_{t-2} + \\theta_1 \\epsilon_{t-1} + \\epsilon_t, \\\\\\ where Y_t is the time series at time t, c is a constant, \\phi_1 and \\phi_2 are the coefficients of the autoregressive terms, \\theta_1 is the coefficient of the moving average term, and \\epsilon_t is the white noise error term at time t.\\\\\\\\nStep 2: The autoregressive component (AR) captures the relationship between an observation and a number of lagged observations. In this case, the AR(2) component means that the current value of the time series depends linearly on the two preceding values plus some error term. This helps in understanding how past values influence future values.\\\\\\\\nStep 3: The moving average component (MA) accounts for the dependency between an observation and the residual errors from previous predictions. Here, the MA(1) component indicates that the current error depends linearly on the previous error term. This allows the model to adjust for random shocks or disturbances in the system. Together, these components allow the ARMA(2,1) model to capture both the autocorrelation in the data and the impact of random shocks over time."
