{
  "answer": "Step 1: To prove that $F[x]$ is a commutative ring with unity, we verify the following properties:\\\\\\\\n- Closure under addition and multiplication: For any $f(x), g(x) \\in F[x]$, both $f(x) + g(x)$ and $f(x) \\cdot g(x)$ are also in $F[x]$. This follows because the sum and product of two polynomials is still a polynomial.\\\\\\\\n- Associativity of addition and multiplication: Polynomial addition and multiplication are associative because these operations are defined component-wise on coefficients, and the underlying field $F$ is associative.\\\\\\\\n- Commutativity of addition and multiplication: Polynomial addition and multiplication are commutative because the corresponding operations in $F$ are commutative.\\\\\\\\n- Existence of additive identity: The zero polynomial serves as the additive identity.\\\\\\\\n- Existence of multiplicative identity: The constant polynomial $1$ serves as the multiplicative identity.\\\\\\\\n- Existence of additive inverses: For any $f(x) \\in F[x]$, its additive inverse is $-f(x)$, which is also in $F[x]$.\\\\\\\\n- Distributive property: Polynomial multiplication distributes over addition because the distributive property holds in $F$.\\\\\\\\nThus, $F[x]$ satisfies all the axioms of a commutative ring with unity.\\\\\\\\nStep 2: To show that $F[x]$ is not a field, we note that not every nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse. Specifically, consider a nonconstant polynomial $f(x) \\in F[x]$. Its degree is positive, and the degree of the product $f(x)g(x)$ is $\\deg(f) + \\deg(g)$. For $f(x)g(x)$ to equal the multiplicative identity $1$, we would require $\\deg(f) + \\deg(g) = 0$, which implies $\\deg(f) = 0$ and $\\deg(g) = 0$. Thus, $f(x)$ cannot have a multiplicative inverse unless it is a constant polynomial. Therefore, $F[x]$ is not a field."
