  "answer": "Step 1: Admissibility in decision theory refers to the property of a decision rule where no other rule dominates it in terms of risk. Specifically, a decision rule δ₂ is considered inadmissible if there exists another decision rule δ₁ such that the risk of δ₁ is less than or equal to the risk of δ₂ for all parameter values θ, with strict inequality holding for at least one θ. Conversely, a decision rule is admissible if no such dominating rule exists.\\nStep 2: An example of an admissible decision rule is the sample mean in the context of estimating the population mean under squared error loss. This is because no other decision rule consistently performs better (i.e., has lower risk) for all possible values of the population mean.\\nStep 3: To justify why the sample mean is admissible, consider that for squared error loss, the risk of an estimator is proportional to its variance. The sample mean minimizes the variance among unbiased estimators, making it optimal in this sense. Any attempt to modify the sample mean to reduce risk would necessarily increase it for some values of the population mean, thus violating the condition for admissibility."
}

