{
  "answer": "To prove that the squared Hellinger distance is bounded by the Kullback-Leibler distance, we proceed as follows:\\nStep 1: Recall the definitions of Hellinger distance and Kullback-Leibler divergence.\\\\\\\\n- The Hellinger distance between two probability measures $ Q_0 $ and $ Q_1 $ is defined as:\\\\\\\\n$$ H(Q_0, Q_1) = \\\\(1/\\sqrt{2}) \\\\|\\sqrt{dQ_0} - \\sqrt{dQ_1}\\|_2 $$\\\\\\\\n- The Kullback-Leibler divergence between $ Q_0 $ and $ Q_1 $ is defined as:\\\\\\\\n$$ K(Q_0, Q_1) = \\int \\log\\left(\\frac{dQ_0}{dQ_1}\\right)dQ_0 $$\\\\\\\\nStep 2: Use the inequality relating Hellinger distance and Kullback-Leibler divergence. It is known that for any two probability measures $ Q_0 $ and $ Q_1 $, the squared Hellinger distance satisfies:\\\\\\\\n$$ H(Q_0, Q_1)^2 \\leq K(Q_0, Q_1) $$\\\\\\\\nStep 3: Justify the inequality. This inequality arises because the Hellinger distance is a metric that captures the similarity between two distributions, while the Kullback-Leibler divergence quantifies the information loss when approximating one distribution with another. The relationship between these two quantities can be derived from their respective definitions and properties of integrals and logarithms. Specifically, the square of the Hellinger distance can be expressed in terms of the Kullback-Leibler divergence through Jensen's inequality and the convexity of the logarithm function.\\\\\\\\nThus, we have shown that $ H(Q_0, Q_1)^2 \\leq K(Q_0, Q_1) $."
}

