{
  "answer": "To prove the equivalence between weak ergodicity for forward products $ T_{p,r} $ and the divergence of the series $ \\sum_{s=0}^{\\infty} [\\phi(H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s})]^{1/2} = \\infty $ for some strictly increasing sequence $ \\{k_s\\} $:\\nStep 1: Recall the definition of weak ergodicity. Weak ergodicity implies that the rows of the matrix $ T_{p,r} $ converge to proportionality as $ r \\to \\infty $. This means that for any two indices $ i $ and $ j $, the ratio $ t_{ik}^{(p,r)} / t_{jk}^{(p,r)} $ converges to a constant $ W_{ij}^{(p)} > 0 $, independent of $ k $.\\\\nStep 2: According to Theorem 3.2, weak ergodicity holds if and only if there exists a strictly increasing sequence $ \\{k_s\\} $ such that the series $ \\sum_{s=0}^{\\infty} [\\phi(H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s})]^{1/2} = \\infty $. Here, $ H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s} $ represents the forward product of matrices over the interval $ [k_s, k_{s+1}] $.\\\\nStep 3: The function $ \\phi(H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s}) $ quantifies the deviation from proportionality in the rows of the matrix $ H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s} $. A larger value of $ \\phi(H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s}) $ indicates greater deviation from proportionality.\\\\nStep 4: The divergence of the series $ \\sum_{s=0}^{\\infty} [\\phi(H_{k_s, k_{s+1} - k_s})]^{1/2} = \\infty $ ensures that the cumulative effect of deviations from proportionality becomes unbounded. This unbounded growth aligns with the condition for weak ergodicity, as it prevents the rows from stabilizing into a fixed proportional relationship.\\\\nStep 5: Therefore, the equivalence arises because the divergence of the series serves as a necessary and sufficient condition for the rows of $ T_{p,r} $ to converge to proportionality, which is the essence of weak ergodicity."
}

