{
  "answer": "To prove that the posterior distribution $\\theta \\mid X = x$ is $\\operatorname{Be}(\\alpha + x, \\beta + n - x)$ when $X \\mid \\theta \\sim {\\mathcal{B}}(n, \\theta)$ and $\\theta \\sim \\operatorname{Be}(\\alpha, \\beta)$, follow these steps:\\nStep 1: Write down the likelihood function $P(X = x \\mid \\theta)$. Since $X \\mid \\theta \\sim {\\mathcal{B}}(n, \\theta)$, the likelihood is given by:\\\\\\ P(X = x \\mid \\theta) = \\binom{n}{x} \\theta^x (1 - \\theta)^{n - x}. \\\\\\ Step 2: Write down the prior distribution $P(\\theta)$. Since $\\theta \\sim \\operatorname{Be}(\\alpha, \\beta)$, the prior is given by:\\\\\\ P(\\theta) = \\frac{\\Gamma(\\alpha + \\beta)}{\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\Gamma(\\beta)} \\theta^{\\alpha - 1} (1 - \\theta)^{\\beta - 1}. \\\\\\ Step 3: Use Bayes' theorem to compute the posterior distribution $P(\\theta \\mid X = x)$. By Bayes' theorem, we have:\\\\\\ P(\\theta \\mid X = x) \\propto P(X = x \\mid \\theta) P(\\theta). \\\\\\ Substituting the expressions for the likelihood and prior, we get:\\\\\\ P(\\theta \\mid X = x) \\propto \\theta^x (1 - \\theta)^{n - x} \\cdot \\theta^{\\alpha - 1} (1 - \\theta)^{\\beta - 1}. \\\\\\ Simplify the expression:\\\\\\ P(\\theta \\mid X = x) \\propto \\theta^{x + \\alpha - 1} (1 - \\theta)^{(n - x) + \\beta - 1}. \\\\\\ Step 4: Recognize the resulting distribution. The above expression corresponds to the kernel of a Beta distribution with parameters $\\alpha + x$ and $\\beta + n - x$. Therefore, the posterior distribution is:\\\\\\ \\theta \\mid X = x \\sim \\operatorname{Be}(\\alpha + x, \\beta + n - x)."
}

