  "answer": "Step 1: Recall the general form of the GLM likelihood function for a single observation $ y_i $: \\\\[ f(y_i; \\theta_i, \\psi) = \\exp\\left\\{ \\frac{y_i \\theta_i - b(\\theta_i)}{a(\\psi)} + c(y_i, \\psi) \\right\\}. \\] Here, $ \\theta_i = X_i^\\top \\beta $ is the linear predictor, and $ G(\\cdot) $ is the link function such that $ \\mu_i = G^{-1}(X_i^\\top \\beta) $. \\\\\\ Step 2: Write the log-likelihood for all observations: \\\\[ l(\\beta) = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\log f(y_i; \\theta_i, \\psi). \\] Substituting the exponential family form gives: \\\\[ l(\\beta) = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\left\\{ \\frac{y_i X_i^\\top \\beta - b(X_i^\\top \\beta)}{a(\\psi)} + c(y_i, \\psi) \\right\\}. \\] \\\\\\ Step 3: Differentiate the log-likelihood with respect to $ \\beta $: \\\\[ \\frac{\\partial l}{\\partial \\beta} = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\frac{y_i - \\mu_i}{a(\\psi)} X_i. \\] Here, $ \\mu_i = G^{-1}(X_i^\\top \\beta) $. \\\\\\ Step 4: To solve for $ \\beta $, use the IRLS algorithm. Start with an initial estimate $ \\beta^{(0)} $. At iteration $ k $: \\\\[ \\mu_i^{(k)} = G^{-1}(X_i^\\top \\beta^{(k)}), \\quad w_i^{(k)} = \\frac{1}{V(\\mu_i^{(k)})}, \\quad z_i^{(k)} = X_i^\\top \\beta^{(k)} + \\frac{y_i - \\mu_i^{(k)}}{f'(\\mu_i^{(k)})}, \\] where $ V(\\mu_i) = b''(\\theta_i) $ is the variance function and $ f'(\\mu_i) = G'(\\eta_i) $. \\\\\\ Step 5: Update $ \\beta^{(k+1)} $ by solving the weighted least squares problem: \\\\[ \\beta^{(k+1)} = (X^\\top W^{(k)} X)^{-1} X^\\top W^{(k)} z^{(k)}, \\] where $ W^{(k)} = \\text{diag}(w_1^{(k)}, \\dots, w_n^{(k)}) $. Repeat until convergence."
}

